00:32:14,716 --> 00:32:20,430
the hand-drawn elements, the
lava explosions. Ted did a lot of that.

684
00:32:22,015 --> 00:32:25,768
PELL: And we sent the layout
group and the effects group on…

685
00:32:25,852 --> 00:32:28,187
MUSKER: We were trying to get
Holt to sign that shot, but it's gone.

686
00:32:28,271 --> 00:32:31,941
PELL: They went on a roller coaster
ride with a camera and took pictures, too.

687
00:32:32,025 --> 00:32:35,153
CLEMENTS: Rasoul actually
went to Magic Mountain

688
00:32:35,237 --> 00:32:36,571
through this part, to do research.

689
00:32:36,655 --> 00:32:38,239
MUSKER: That's an amusement park here.

690
00:32:38,323 --> 00:32:40,409
CLEMENTS: Yeah, in California.

691
00:32:44,329 --> 00:32:47,081
-'Cause the feeling was to be…
-MUSKER: He left the lens cap on.

692
00:32:47,165 --> 00:32:50,836
CLEMENTS: He had to go through
twice because he left the lens cap on.

693
00:32:50,961 --> 00:32:55,257
But we really wanted this to be kind
of a roller coaster ride for the audience.

694
00:32:56,716 --> 00:32:59,218
Some of these effects
are pretty standard now,

695
00:32:59,302 --> 00:33:01,095
but at the time they were innovative

696
00:33:01,179 --> 00:33:04,182
and nothing like that had
ever been done before.

697
00:33:05,684 --> 00:33:08,811
This is probably the biggest
effects sequence in the movie.

698
00:33:08,895 --> 00:33:11,898
I always liked this shot of the tiger in,

699
00:33:11,982 --> 00:33:13,441
and in terms of Aladdin's cue,

700
00:33:13,525 --> 00:33:16,569
I think that the music
through that is really good.

701
00:33:16,653 --> 00:33:18,154
MUSKER: Yeah, Alan
Menken did the underscore

702
00:33:18,238 --> 00:33:19,280
for the movie as well as the songs,

703
00:33:19,364 --> 00:33:24,118
so this gave him a chance to
strut his action-adventure stuff here.

704
00:33:24,202 --> 00:33:27,163
CLEMENTS: Two Academy
Awards, for both Song and Score.

705
00:33:27,247 --> 00:33:28,582
<i>First give me the lamp.</i>

706
00:33:32,420 --> 00:33:34,589
[MANIACAL LAUGHTER]

707
00:33:35,673 --> 00:33:39,051
CLEMENTS: We didn't talk earlier
about that first shot of the lamp.

708
00:33:39,135 --> 00:33:41,762
How many times we redid
that first shot of the lamp.

709
00:33:41,846 --> 00:33:44,014
MUSKER: I don't know what the
problem was, but it took… Oh, that.

710
00:33:44,098 --> 00:33:45,849
This one, too, when
he was handing it off,

711
00:33:45,933 --> 00:33:47,783
took a lot, but I can't remember why.

712
00:33:48,728 --> 00:33:51,814
PELL: That was a discussion
about the close-up of his eyes,

713
00:33:51,898 --> 00:33:53,273
of Aladdin's eyes.

714
00:33:53,357 --> 00:33:56,151
How to get at a more
emotional moment in here.

715
00:33:56,235 --> 00:34:00,865
Just by adding that close-up,
it added just what was needed.

716
00:34:05,244 --> 00:34:07,955
[ROARING]

717
00:34:15,046 --> 00:34:17,756
MUSKER: We wanted this
contrast after all that racket

718
00:34:17,840 --> 00:34:21,677
to have this moment of near
silence while the track disappears.

719
00:34:21,761 --> 00:34:24,012
<i>I… Where is it?</i>

720
00:34:24,096 --> 00:34:25,431
<i>No.</i>

721
00:34:25,765 --> 00:34:28,267
<i>No!</i>

722
00:34:30,394 --> 00:34:32,396
CLEMENTS: So this scene actually was one

723
00:34:32,480 --> 00:34:34,398
of the last scenes added in the movie.

724
00:34:34,482 --> 00:34:37,532
It wasn't there for a long time.
It was a controversial scene.

725
00:34:38,194 --> 00:34:40,904
I think Jeffrey wanted this
scene particularly because

726
00:34:40,988 --> 00:34:43,866
he felt we'd been away from
Jasmine and the Sultan too long

727
00:34:43,950 --> 00:34:45,742
and we needed to get back to that.

728
00:34:45,826 --> 00:34:48,704
At the time, I think, because we
were in such pressure on length,

729
00:34:48,788 --> 00:34:50,873
we weren't sure it was necessary.

730
00:34:50,957 --> 00:34:54,918
But in retrospect, I kind of feel
like it was probably a good idea

731
00:34:55,002 --> 00:34:58,352
-just to bring that thread back in.
-MUSKER: Remind us of her story.

732
00:34:58,589 --> 00:35:01,967
PELL: And I think more so this segment

733
00:35:02,051 --> 00:35:04,761
is where you see Aladdin
change in his design

734
00:35:04,845 --> 00:35:07,139
'cause this was the
earliest in production.

735
00:35:07,223 --> 00:35:09,391
And Aladdin started out
looking a little younger,

736
00:35:09,475 --> 00:35:16,148
and we realized once Jasmine was
designed and was looking so spiffy

737
00:35:16,274 --> 00:35:19,234
that she wouldn't be attracted
to a young-looking Aladdin,

738
00:35:19,318 --> 00:35:21,361
so we aged him up.

739
00:35:21,445 --> 00:35:22,863
CLEMENTS: Originally,
we were thinking of him

740
00:35:22,947 --> 00:35:24,740
as kind of a Michael J. Fox-type.

741
00:35:24,824 --> 00:35:27,327
And then Jeffrey said,
"No, he's Tom Cruise,"

742
00:35:27,411 --> 00:35:31,498
and we kind of went through a
little bit of a Tom Cruise makeover.

743
00:35:32,666 --> 00:35:34,417
Of course, there's a lot
of makeovers nowadays,

744
00:35:34,501 --> 00:35:36,251
-but that was hard.
-[PELL LAUGHING]

745
00:35:36,920 --> 00:35:38,922
PELL: It wasn't an extreme makeover.

746
00:35:39,006 --> 00:35:42,306
CLEMENTS: But the cleanup people
had to remake him in this section.

747
00:35:43,343 --> 00:35:47,389
And here he comes, the Genie of the Lamp.

748
00:35:49,349 --> 00:35:51,351
MUSKER: And Eric Goldberg,
the lead animator on the Genie,

749
00:35:51,435 --> 00:35:53,561
who designed the Genie
and helped sell the concept,

750
00:35:53,645 --> 00:35:55,939
really pushed us in this… Al Hirschfeld,

751
00:35:56,023 --> 00:35:57,941
the noted caricaturist
of The New York Times,

752
00:35:58,025 --> 00:35:59,692
Eric was a huge fan of his

753
00:35:59,776 --> 00:36:02,278
and he really was influenced
by that in designing the Genie,

754
00:36:02,362 --> 00:36:05,112
and that fed into the other
designs of the film as well.

755
00:36:05,407 --> 00:36:08,493
CLEMENTS: I think Robin Williams…
One of the first ideas

756
00:36:08,577 --> 00:36:10,036
that we had on the movie was actually

757
00:36:10,120 --> 00:36:12,747
that Robin Williams could
be the voice of the Genie,

758
00:36:12,831 --> 00:36:15,291
and it was a big question of whether
we would be able to get him or not.

759
00:36:15,375 --> 00:36:19,379
We actually wrote the first version
of the script with Robin in mind.

760
00:36:20,255 --> 00:36:23,800
A lot of people wonder, "How
much of Robin was ad-libbed?"

761
00:36:23,884 --> 00:36:26,344
And the truth is not a single word.

762
00:36:26,428 --> 00:36:30,515
It was all written almost to the syllable
and he followed the script exactly.

763
00:36:30,599 --> 00:36:32,559
MUSKER: He's lying through his teeth.

764
00:36:33,060 --> 00:36:36,646
CLEMENTS: It actually was
written to begin with in a Robin form,

765
00:36:36,730 --> 00:36:39,732
but then Robin would
take the script as written

766
00:36:39,816 --> 00:36:42,694
and do it a few times, and
then start just playing with it

767
00:36:42,778 --> 00:36:46,114
and improvising and coming
up with so much material,

768
00:36:46,198 --> 00:36:47,657
so much great material, of course.

769
00:36:47,741 --> 00:36:50,618
Isn't that the Governor of California?

770
00:36:50,702 --> 00:36:52,161
MUSKER: The Governator? Yeah.

771
00:36:52,245 --> 00:36:53,580
Well, there were
discussions at the beginning,

772
00:36:53,664 --> 00:36:55,832
how close, when Robin
does his celebrity voice,

773
00:36:55,916 --> 00:36:57,709
should we caricature that person?

774
00:36:57,793 --> 00:36:59,877
At first, we were more reticent,

775
00:36:59,961 --> 00:37:02,756
and then we realized,
upon prodding from Eric,

776
00:37:02,881 --> 00:37:05,341
I think, that's part of the
fun of all this, even though…

777
00:37:05,425 --> 00:37:08,011
CLEMENTS: No one will
know who Ed Sullivan is.

778
00:37:08,095 --> 00:37:10,513
PELL: Yes, it doesn't matter.
They're just a funny character.

779
00:37:10,597 --> 00:37:12,390
CLEMENTS: But, yeah,
we found people laughed

780
00:37:12,474 --> 00:37:14,424
even if they didn't get the references.

781
00:37:16,144 --> 00:37:17,478
MUSKER: And they could
understand the cash register,

782
00:37:17,562 --> 00:37:20,662
but they might not get Groucho
Marx here, or You Bet Your Life.

783
00:37:21,943 --> 00:37:24,445
So Robin singing here
was a new thing for him.

784
00:37:24,529 --> 00:37:27,031
I don't believe he had ever sung.
Well, no, Popeye, he had sung,

785
00:37:27,115 --> 00:37:30,826
but kind of the narrow
band of musicality.

786
00:37:30,910 --> 00:37:32,786
PELL: It wasn't the thing he
was most comfortable with.

787
00:37:32,870 --> 00:37:34,705
CLEMENTS: We were
thinking, sure, Robin can sing

788
00:37:34,789 --> 00:37:36,248
'cause he can imitate anything,

789
00:37:36,332 --> 00:37:38,167
so all he has to do is imitate a singer,

790
00:37:38,251 --> 00:37:40,794
but he was a little
nervous about the singing

791
00:37:40,878 --> 00:37:42,588
and really worked hard on it.

792
00:37:42,672 --> 00:37:45,049
MUSKER: We worked with David
Friedman, our musical director.

793
00:37:45,133 --> 00:37:47,509
Robin would rehearse in the
evenings after shooting all day

794
00:37:47,593 --> 00:37:49,136
and doing test footage for Hook,

795
00:37:49,220 --> 00:37:51,305
where he was hung on wires and exhausted.

796
00:37:51,389 --> 00:37:54,391
He was staying at Barry Levinson's
house in Beverly Hills, I think,

797
00:37:54,475 --> 00:37:57,227
and we would go there at 9:00
or 10:00 at night with the piano,

798
00:37:57,311 --> 00:37:58,646
and he'd be, "No, go ahead. That's fine."

799
00:37:58,730 --> 00:38:01,940
CLEMENTS: He'd drag in just
looking completely exhausted,

800
00:38:02,024 --> 00:38:05,569
like the last thing he ever wanted
to do was rehearse these songs,

801
00:38:05,653 --> 00:38:08,405
but then he pulled this
energy from somewhere

802
00:38:08,489 --> 00:38:10,950
and he'd be great.

803
00:38:11,325 --> 00:38:13,869
MUSKER: He threw himself into it,
and the lyrics on this song are so great,

804
00:38:13,953 --> 00:38:15,746
Howard Ashman lyrics,

805
00:38:15,830 --> 00:38:17,665
just one gag after
another on these lines.

806
00:38:17,749 --> 00:38:21,085
It plays with food. Howard's
lyrics often had fun with food jokes,

807
00:38:21,169 --> 00:38:22,962
baklava and all this.

808
00:38:23,337 --> 00:38:26,799
PELL: I also think one of the ways that
you made Robin feel more comfortable

809
00:38:26,883 --> 00:38:29,677
would be to say,
"Sing it with an accent."

810
00:38:29,844 --> 00:38:32,471
-Sing it again with a different accent.
-MUSKER: He could shift personas.

811
00:38:32,555 --> 00:38:34,598
We had a little section
where he's a western guy

812
00:38:34,682 --> 00:38:36,433
and he was Cab Calloway.

813
00:38:36,517 --> 00:38:38,310
CLEMENTS: It was the
same thing as the dialogue,

814
00:38:38,394 --> 00:38:40,771
he would sing it different each time

815
00:38:40,855 --> 00:38:43,316
and try different things
each time he sang it.

816
00:38:44,192 --> 00:38:46,242
PELL: We should also mention Danny Troob.

817
00:38:47,111 --> 00:38:48,987
MUSKER: Danny Troob's
orchestrations on this, and really…

818
00:38:49,071 --> 00:38:51,699
CLEMENTS: Throughout the
whole movie, but this is some of the…

819
00:38:51,783 --> 00:38:54,118
MUSKER: The original demo
of this was just a piano track,

820
00:38:54,202 --> 00:38:57,121
and then Danny Troob went wild

821
00:38:57,205 --> 00:38:59,832
with the big, brassy sound of this thing.

822
00:38:59,916 --> 00:39:01,792
It became bigger in scale,

823
00:39:01,876 --> 00:39:05,505
and so the visuals had to come
up to the scale of his orchestra.

824
00:39:05,630 --> 00:39:09,049
PELL: The music talent was amazing.
Between Tim Rice

825
00:39:09,133 --> 00:39:12,261
and Howard Ashman and Alan Menken
and David Friedman and Danny Troob,

826
00:39:12,345 --> 00:39:15,723
we really had an incredible,
incredible team on this show.

827
00:39:18,185 --> 00:39:20,312
-This took a lot of animation.
-[CHUCKLING]

828
00:39:21,146 --> 00:39:23,898
And this was the first
sequence we did complete,

829
00:39:23,982 --> 00:39:27,652
and it served as kind of motivation
for all the animators on the picture

830
00:39:27,736 --> 00:39:30,822
because it's so energetic
and just works so well.

831
00:39:30,906 --> 00:39:33,491
CLEMENTS: And it got shown
outside of the studio a little bit.

832
00:39:33,575 --> 00:39:37,287
I know that it was screened
at CalArts and other places.

833
00:39:37,371 --> 00:39:39,706
And I think it got a great reaction,

834
00:39:39,790 --> 00:39:43,793
and just the reaction to this sequence
really was encouraging to everybody,

835
00:39:43,877 --> 00:39:46,922
that this whole idea might actually work.

836
00:39:47,631 --> 00:39:49,048
MUSKER: We struggled
with the end of the song, too,

837
00:39:49,132 --> 00:39:50,341
trying to get the
appropriate button for it.

838
00:39:50,425 --> 00:39:52,469
I think it was Eric who
just, "Just forget it."

839
00:39:52,553 --> 00:39:55,680
"Just stick an applause sign in.
He's so shameless, it's possible."

840
00:39:55,764 --> 00:39:58,266
I'm like, "You know what?
You're right. That's the way to do it."

841
00:39:58,350 --> 00:39:59,560
<i>Ah, almost.</i>

842
00:39:59,935 --> 00:40:02,685
MUSKER: Kids in the audience,
that's William F. Buckley.

843
00:40:02,813 --> 00:40:03,939
<i>Like?</i>

844
00:40:04,106 --> 00:40:07,192
<i>Ah, rule number one,
I can't kill anybody.</i>

845
00:40:07,276 --> 00:40:08,610
<i>So don't ask.</i>

846
00:40:08,694 --> 00:40:09,945
<i>Rule number two.</i>

847
00:40:10,612 --> 00:40:12,572
MUSKER: And he does
Peter Lorre coming up here,

848
00:40:12,656 --> 00:40:16,701
but in this case, we just made him
look like a big grotesque guy, and not…

849
00:40:16,785 --> 00:40:18,286
You have a little Yiddish there.

850
00:40:18,370 --> 00:40:19,746
You got the whole shebang there.

851
00:40:19,830 --> 00:40:22,540
Eric had to explain to us the
Yiddish, us Catholic yo-yos

852
00:40:22,624 --> 00:40:24,224
that don't know what ponems are.

853
00:40:24,459 --> 00:40:26,503
<i>Other than that, you got it.</i>

854
00:40:26,670 --> 00:40:28,046
<i>-Hmm.
-Oh!</i>

855
00:40:28,130 --> 00:40:30,924
CLEMENTS: And this Robert De Niro bit

856
00:40:31,008 --> 00:40:33,635
that the Genie goes
into here was a lot longer,

857
00:40:33,719 --> 00:40:36,471
and Robin was having
so much fun with this.

858
00:40:36,847 --> 00:40:38,973
It would have been
funny to use the whole bit

859
00:40:39,057 --> 00:40:40,809
'cause he went on this extended rant

860
00:40:40,893 --> 00:40:43,561
that was one of the most
hilarious things I've ever seen.

861
00:40:43,645 --> 00:40:46,731
But we couldn't use the whole bit,
but I think we still used enough of it

862
00:40:46,815 --> 00:40:48,817
that you get it pretty well.

863
00:40:48,901 --> 00:40:50,360
<i>Did you rub my lamp?</i>

864
00:40:50,444 --> 00:40:51,945
<i>Did you wake me up?</i>

865
00:40:52,029 --> 00:40:53,738
MUSKER: Robin's a
friend of Robert De Niro.

866
00:40:53,822 --> 00:40:56,574
CLEMENTS: Yeah, he had just done…
What was the film with Robert De Niro?

867
00:40:56,658 --> 00:40:58,827
PELL: Awakenings.
CLEMENTS: Awakenings. Right.

868
00:40:58,911 --> 00:41:01,454
So he had Robert De Niro on the brain.

869
00:41:01,538 --> 00:41:04,249
MUSKER: We did see this film
with Martin Scorsese in New York,

870
00:41:04,333 --> 00:41:07,335
and were watching his reaction
as this was going to come up

871
00:41:07,419 --> 00:41:08,628
and he was laughing quite a bit.

872
00:41:08,712 --> 00:41:11,297
So we thought it was okay that we had…

873
00:41:11,381 --> 00:41:14,177
He was amused that it
was Robert De Niro there.

874
00:41:15,803 --> 00:41:18,597
PELL: I think it's important,
while we're in the Sultan's castle,

875
00:41:18,681 --> 00:41:21,100
while it's still under
the Sultan's reign,

876
00:41:21,184 --> 00:41:23,185
that you look at the color and the shapes

877
00:41:23,269 --> 00:41:25,604
-of the pillars and the backgrounds.
-MUSKER: The background painting.

878
00:41:25,688 --> 00:41:27,314
CLEMENTS: This background
is one of the most beautiful

879
00:41:27,398 --> 00:41:29,400
backgrounds in the movie.

880
00:41:29,484 --> 00:41:33,028
Ian Gooding, who we've
worked with on other films as well,

881
00:41:33,112 --> 00:41:34,906
painted this background.

882
00:41:35,239 --> 00:41:38,200
MUSKER: Jasmine's outfit,
this mint greenish outfit,

883
00:41:38,284 --> 00:41:40,953
came from Persian miniatures.
It was Richard's suggestion

884
00:41:41,037 --> 00:41:43,956
to use that. We liked it. Of course Amy,
who's sitting here, she won't mention it,

885
00:41:44,040 --> 00:41:45,958
but she gave us such a hard
time about that bare midriff,

886
00:41:46,042 --> 00:41:47,877
but ultimately she…

887
00:41:49,629 --> 00:41:52,279
CLEMENTS: This has sort of
become a fashion statement.

888
00:41:53,049 --> 00:41:54,758
PELL: And I think you did it.

889
00:41:54,842 --> 00:41:57,428
-You affected fashion from…
-MUSKER: Yeah, all these younger…

890
00:41:57,512 --> 00:41:59,763
My daughter now has the
bare midriff that I can't stand.

891
00:41:59,847 --> 00:42:00,848
PELL: That's right. It's because of you.

892
00:42:00,932 --> 00:42:02,141
MUSKER: I should've listened to you.

893
00:42:02,225 --> 00:42:03,875
-[ALL LAUGHING]
-Boy, was I wrong.

894
00:42:04,102 --> 00:42:05,936
<i>I had gotten that lamp.</i>

895
00:42:06,020 --> 00:42:09,107
<i>"I will have the power
to get rid of you."</i>

896
00:42:09,565 --> 00:42:11,358
MUSKER: When Gilbert did this imitation,

897
00:42:11,442 --> 00:42:13,152
I couldn't believe how accurate that was.

898
00:42:13,236 --> 00:42:14,236
[CHUCKLING]

899
00:42:14,320 --> 00:42:16,363
Yes, that was Gilbert's tour de force,

900
00:42:16,447 --> 00:42:18,866
him imitating Linda Larkin as Jasmine.

901
00:42:19,200 --> 00:42:22,996
<i>Only until she finds a chump husband.</i>

902
00:42:23,246 --> 00:42:24,914
<i>Then she'll have us banished.</i>

903
00:42:25,832 --> 00:42:27,583
<i>Or beheaded.</i>

904
00:42:27,709 --> 00:42:29,210
BOTH: <i>Eww!</i>

905
00:42:29,585 --> 00:42:32,630
MUSKER: That's our
homage to Lucille Ball there.

906
00:42:32,714 --> 00:42:35,549
<i>What if you were the chump husband?</i>

907
00:42:35,633 --> 00:42:36,842
<i>What?</i>

908
00:42:36,926 --> 00:42:38,552
<i>Okay, you marry…</i>

909
00:42:38,636 --> 00:42:40,804
MUSKER: When we
recorded Gilbert, as I recall,

910
00:42:40,888 --> 00:42:42,765
they had to back away the microphones

911
00:42:42,890 --> 00:42:47,311
'cause he's a diminutive
guy, but a powerful performer.

912
00:42:48,271 --> 00:42:50,105
<i>I become the sultan.</i>

913
00:42:50,189 --> 00:42:54,026
<i>-The idea has merit.
-Yes, merit. Yes.</i>

914
00:42:54,110 --> 00:43:00,616
<i>And then we drop papa-in-law
and the little woman off a cliff.</i>

915
00:43:00,783 --> 00:43:02,744
<i>Yaaah!</i>

916
00:43:03,119 --> 00:43:05,621
CLEMENTS: The guys
really enjoyed this laughing bit.

917
00:43:05,705 --> 00:43:08,416
They actually recorded that
with the two of them together.

918
00:43:08,500 --> 00:43:10,710
MUSKER: They would laugh
for about 15 minutes straight.

919
00:43:10,794 --> 00:43:13,130
[CHUCKLING] They just went on and on.

920
00:43:19,386 --> 00:43:20,512
MUSKER: This is our oasis sequence.

921
00:43:20,596 --> 00:43:22,555
This is one of our simpler
sequences, arguably,

922
00:43:22,639 --> 00:43:24,182
in that we didn't have a lot of effects

923
00:43:24,266 --> 00:43:26,351
-and it was a little simpler.
-CLEMENTS: Rasoul was really happy

924
00:43:26,435 --> 00:43:28,979
'cause the same background
is used over and over and over.

925
00:43:29,063 --> 00:43:32,816
But its fine, and it saved us some money,

926
00:43:34,026 --> 00:43:36,276
and it's a nice background,
so it looks great.

927
00:43:36,403 --> 00:43:38,238
<i>Now, about my three wishes.</i>

928
00:43:38,322 --> 00:43:40,573
CLEMENTS: This was, there
again, Ted and Terry's thing

929
00:43:40,657 --> 00:43:43,576
of how they could get out of
that thing and not use up a wish.

930
00:43:43,660 --> 00:43:45,287
It solved a big problem.

931
00:43:45,496 --> 00:43:48,915
In the earlier version of Aladdin,
we had the idea of unlimited wishes,

932
00:43:48,999 --> 00:43:51,626
which is actually the way it
is in the Arabian Nights story,

933
00:43:51,710 --> 00:43:54,254
which was the idea that
once you get a genie,

934
00:43:54,338 --> 00:43:56,715
you can just wish for as
many things as you want.

935
00:43:56,799 --> 00:44:00,343
The good thing about that is
from a visual fantasy standpoint,

936
00:44:00,427 --> 00:44:01,553
you can do a lot.

937
00:44:01,678 --> 00:44:04,305
You can do anything you
want, as long as you want.

938
00:44:04,389 --> 00:44:08,059
But I think rightfully, in terms
of the adjustments to the story,

939
00:44:08,143 --> 00:44:11,479
the three wishes seemed
better and became important,

940
00:44:11,563 --> 00:44:14,899
but the challenge was then to
figure out ways within the three wishes

941
00:44:14,983 --> 00:44:18,236
that we could still get all
of the fantasy and magic.

942
00:44:18,320 --> 00:44:20,280
By going with three
wishes, it raised the stakes,

943
00:44:20,364 --> 00:44:21,990
so each wish was really important.

944
00:44:22,074 --> 00:44:26,494
It gave a rising action to
the movie where the climax…

945
00:44:26,578 --> 00:44:28,872
When you're down to your last
wish, it would have more import.

946
00:44:28,956 --> 00:44:31,207
The ending wouldn't work if
he could have a million wishes.

947
00:44:31,291 --> 00:44:33,293
The ending really became more powerful

948
00:44:33,377 --> 00:44:35,295
when he only had one left to use.

949
00:44:35,379 --> 00:44:36,963
MUSKER: He can't wish for more wishes,

950
00:44:37,047 --> 00:44:39,591
that was one of the rules, so
you couldn't get around it that way.

951
00:44:39,675 --> 00:44:42,135
<i>Such a thing would be
greater than all the magic</i>

952
00:44:42,219 --> 00:44:43,803
<i>and all the treasures…</i>

953
00:44:43,887 --> 00:44:47,057
CLEMENTS: The question
with the Genie, as broad as he is,

954
00:44:47,141 --> 00:44:48,892
I think we wanted the audience to feel

955
00:44:48,976 --> 00:44:53,105
that this really meant something to him.
His freedom was really important.

956
00:44:54,523 --> 00:44:58,652
I think Robin did a good job of
selling the sincerity of the things,

957
00:44:58,777 --> 00:45:00,737
when the Genie had to be sincere.

958
00:45:03,283 --> 00:45:05,826
-This is a great bit.
-[CHUCKLING]

959
00:45:05,910 --> 00:45:08,913
Robin threw that in,
that little Pinocchio bit.

960
00:45:08,997 --> 00:45:10,664
MUSKER: And Eric really picked up on it.

961
00:45:10,748 --> 00:45:12,666
PELL: And it got so…

962
00:45:12,750 --> 00:45:15,127
The laughter was so
strong the first preview

963
00:45:15,211 --> 00:45:17,004
that we actually had to
add a few seconds to it.

964
00:45:17,088 --> 00:45:18,130
MUSKER: You're right.

965
00:45:18,214 --> 00:45:19,507
CLEMENTS: There were
several places like that,

966
00:45:19,591 --> 00:45:21,342
which I guess is a good problem to have,

967
00:45:21,426 --> 00:45:24,553
but there were several
cases after the first preview

968
00:45:24,637 --> 00:45:26,639
where the audience laughed
so hard at certain things,

969
00:45:26,723 --> 00:45:29,141
you missed huge stretches of dialogue.

970
00:45:29,225 --> 00:45:32,103
So we had to try to open things up,

971
00:45:32,187 --> 00:45:34,563
so you could at least get some of it.

972
00:45:34,647 --> 00:45:36,065
<i>And this hair. Wow.</i>

973
00:45:36,149 --> 00:45:38,318
<i>And her smile…</i> [SIGHS]

974
00:45:38,776 --> 00:45:39,944
Ami.

975
00:45:40,486 --> 00:45:42,238
C'est l'amour.

976
00:45:42,322 --> 00:45:44,365
<i>But she's the princess.</i>

977
00:45:44,449 --> 00:45:46,826
<i>To even have a chance, I'd have to be…</i>

978
00:45:46,910 --> 00:45:49,704
<i>Hey, can you make me a prince?</i>

979
00:45:50,038 --> 00:45:52,456
CLEMENTS: This is actually
some of the first Aladdin animation

980
00:45:52,540 --> 00:45:54,542
done in the Tom Cruise mode,

981
00:45:54,626 --> 00:45:58,338
as I remember, that this was
where he got his makeover.

982
00:45:59,088 --> 00:46:01,674
PELL: So we just passed…

983
00:46:01,758 --> 00:46:03,408
MUSKER: Sebastian making a cameo?

984
00:46:04,969 --> 00:46:09,306
PELL: You try to have some inside jokes.

985
00:46:09,390 --> 00:46:13,060
CLEMENTS: And then Alan threw
in a little homage to Under the Sea

986
00:46:13,144 --> 00:46:16,730
in the underscore, too, which
helped the audience get it.

987
00:46:16,814 --> 00:46:18,899
MUSKER: In every
animated film we've done,

988
00:46:18,983 --> 00:46:20,568
we've tried to find an angle

989
00:46:20,652 --> 00:46:23,195
that makes it better to do an
animation than a live action.

990
00:46:23,279 --> 00:46:24,822
Certainly in these days of digital stuff,

991
00:46:24,906 --> 00:46:26,907
that line has gotten
blurrier and blurrier.

992
00:46:26,991 --> 00:46:29,451
But certainly then we said, "How
can we do the Genie in a way"

993
00:46:29,535 --> 00:46:31,078
"that they wouldn't
have done in any of the"

994
00:46:31,162 --> 00:46:34,331
"live-action film adaptations of it?
What can we do with that character,"

995
00:46:34,415 --> 00:46:37,251
"as well as others like the
carpet, that you just wouldn't do?"

996
00:46:37,335 --> 00:46:41,589
So that's why we really thought
Robin was ideal, with his mimicry,

997
00:46:41,673 --> 00:46:46,093
his speed, his quickness,
his improvisational ability.

998
00:46:46,177 --> 00:46:47,636
It's great to have an
improviser in animation

999
00:46:47,720 --> 00:46:49,763
because the voice is
always recorded first,

1000
00:46:49,847 --> 00:46:52,975
so whatever he comes up with,
we can write around and write to.

1001
00:46:53,059 --> 00:46:55,853
CLEMENTS: But it was risky,
too, and I think we knew that

1002
00:46:55,937 --> 00:46:58,148
'cause we knew we were a
little bit jumping off the cliff.

1003
00:46:58,232 --> 00:47:01,484
Because in order for that to
work, the film had to be a comedy

1004
00:47:01,568 --> 00:47:05,697
and it had to have a tone that
was a little bit looser, I think,

1005
00:47:05,781 --> 00:47:08,867
than any Disney film that
had been done up to that point.

1006
00:47:08,951 --> 00:47:11,161
GENIE: <i>He's got the outfit.
He's got the elephant.</i>

1007
00:47:11,245 --> 00:47:13,246
<i>But we're not through yet.</i>

1008
00:47:13,330 --> 00:47:17,835
<i>Hang on to your turban, kid.
We're gonna make you a star.</i>

1009
00:47:18,252 --> 00:47:20,629
CLEMENTS: So if you look
closely, you can see the Beast there.

1010
00:47:20,713 --> 00:47:22,881
We're just passing him now,
from Beauty and the Beast.

1011
00:47:22,965 --> 00:47:25,717
MUSKER: Rewind that and look at it,
you'll find the Beast in that pile of toys

1012
00:47:25,801 --> 00:47:27,802
that he just stacked up there.

1013
00:47:27,886 --> 00:47:29,638
<i>A solution to the problem
with your daughter.</i>

1014
00:47:29,722 --> 00:47:32,766
<i>Awk. The problem with your daughter.</i>

1015
00:47:32,933 --> 00:47:34,643
<i>Oh, really?</i>

1016
00:47:34,727 --> 00:47:36,061
<i>Right here.</i>

1017
00:47:36,729 --> 00:47:39,940
CLEMENTS: I think Rasoul was in
charge of any of the Arabic writing,

1018
00:47:40,024 --> 00:47:42,901
-like on this scroll.
-MUSKER: Is it real? I don't remember.

1019
00:47:42,985 --> 00:47:44,319
CLEMENTS: I don't
think the scroll is real,

1020
00:47:44,403 --> 00:47:47,864
but there are places where
we do have real Arabic writing,

1021
00:47:47,948 --> 00:47:51,284
and we were always nervous
that there might be something said

1022
00:47:51,368 --> 00:47:56,915
that someone in Iran might
read and be concerned about, yes.

1023
00:47:56,999 --> 00:48:00,419
<i>"A princess must then be wed to…"</i>

1024
00:48:01,587 --> 00:48:04,089
<i>Hmm. Interesting.</i>

1025
00:48:04,214 --> 00:48:05,882
<i>What? Who?</i>

1026
00:48:05,966 --> 00:48:07,509
<i>The royal vizier.</i>

1027
00:48:07,593 --> 00:48:10,929
<i>Why, that would be me.</i>

1028
00:48:12,848 --> 00:48:16,298
CLEMENTS: No, I don't think that's
genuine Arabic writing. [CHUCKLING]

1029
00:48:16,643 --> 00:48:18,645
MUSKER: No, I think it might…
Maybe Rasoul did it.

1030
00:48:18,729 --> 00:48:20,314
I don't remember now.

1031
00:48:23,525 --> 00:48:25,652
We have our Don Paul effects here

1032
00:48:25,736 --> 00:48:29,739
with the squiggles in the snake's eyes.

1033
00:48:29,823 --> 00:48:34,370
<i>I will order the princess to…</i>

1034
00:48:35,037 --> 00:48:37,372
<i>But you're so old.</i>

1035
00:48:37,456 --> 00:48:39,332
<i>The princess will marry me.</i>

1036
00:48:39,416 --> 00:48:41,209
MUSKER: I did do a
caricature of this scene

1037
00:48:41,293 --> 00:48:43,670
with Ron and I as the Sultan and Jafar,

1038
00:48:43,754 --> 00:48:45,630
talking about making
changes to the movie.

1039
00:48:45,714 --> 00:48:46,799
CLEMENTS: Oh, yeah.

1040
00:48:49,301 --> 00:48:51,011
MUSKER: Now this is this
great song that Howard and Alan…

1041
00:48:51,095 --> 00:48:55,474
Howard did write this new
song for this version of Aladdin,

1042
00:48:55,558 --> 00:48:58,894
and threw everything from
every Macy's Day Parade he could

1043
00:48:58,978 --> 00:49:01,689
into the whole production value of it.

1044
00:49:01,773 --> 00:49:04,233
CLEMENTS: We looked at Cleopatra
and other things for inspiration.

1045
00:49:04,317 --> 00:49:07,528
MUSKER: There was originally a long intro

1046
00:49:07,612 --> 00:49:10,114
that we cut out and we
went right to the song.

1047
00:49:10,198 --> 00:49:13,451
PELL: When we recorded
this, Robin Williams came in

1048
00:49:13,535 --> 00:49:15,536
and he made up a song
called Prince Jeffrey.

1049
00:49:15,620 --> 00:49:17,705
MUSKER: Oh, yeah, that's right.
CLEMENTS: Oh, yes, that's right.

1050
00:49:17,789 --> 00:49:19,123
We should get that.

1051
00:49:19,207 --> 00:49:20,624
PELL: And he was
making it up on the spot.

1052
00:49:20,708 --> 00:49:22,585
It was so impressive.

1053
00:49:22,669 --> 00:49:24,587
[GENIE SINGING] Prince Ali, fabulous he

1054
00:49:24,671 --> 00:49:27,923
CLEMENTS: Yeah, this was Howard Ashman.

1055
00:49:28,007 --> 00:49:29,884
This was, I think, the only
song we used in the movie

1056
00:49:29,968 --> 00:49:33,596
that was written after Howard
had gotten sick, but before he died.

1057
00:49:33,680 --> 00:49:34,972
But it's one of the best songs.

1058
00:49:35,056 --> 00:49:37,767
Even though Howard was very
sick when he wrote this song,

1059
00:49:37,851 --> 00:49:40,186
he did a fantastic job on it.

1060
00:49:41,521 --> 00:49:46,192
[SINGING] Prince Ali,
mighty is he Ali Ababwa

1061
00:49:46,985 --> 00:49:50,279
CLEMENTS: Sort of a press agent.
The Genie is Aladdin's press agent

1062
00:49:50,363 --> 00:49:55,493
and is selling him to
the people of Agrabah.

1063
00:49:57,745 --> 00:50:00,081
MUSKER: We divide the
movie up, Ron and I do.

1064
00:50:00,165 --> 00:50:02,291
When we are directing it,

1065
00:50:02,375 --> 00:50:05,002
we pick different sequences
in the film, so Ron did this one.

1066
00:50:05,086 --> 00:50:06,462
For example, I had done Friend Like Me,

1067
00:50:06,546 --> 00:50:09,507
this was Ron's tour de force here.

1068
00:50:10,383 --> 00:50:13,887
CLEMENTS: We both
got to do one Genie song.

1069
00:50:14,304 --> 00:50:16,180
Has he got a zoo I'm telling you

1070
00:50:16,264 --> 00:50:18,558
It's a world-class menagerie

1071
00:50:19,350 --> 00:50:21,268
CLEMENTS: I'm sure all kids
know who Ethel Merman is,

1072
00:50:21,352 --> 00:50:24,814
-but this is the Genie as Ethel Merman.
-[CHUCKLING]

1073
00:50:24,898 --> 00:50:26,816
Robin would pretty much come up

1074
00:50:26,900 --> 00:50:30,736
with those different
personalities himself,

1075
00:50:30,820 --> 00:50:33,156
and then we'd find visuals to go with it.

1076
00:50:36,743 --> 00:50:38,994
You can see that Jasmine is not shallow

1077
00:50:39,078 --> 00:50:41,497
-like a lot of..
-MUSKER: We are.

1078
00:50:41,581 --> 00:50:44,333
[SINGING] And to view
them he charges no fee

1079
00:50:44,417 --> 00:50:45,960
He's generous So generous

1080
00:50:46,044 --> 00:50:48,547
He's got slaves He's
got servants and flunkies

1081
00:50:48,631 --> 00:50:50,132
MUSKER: The lyrics to this are great.

1082
00:50:50,216 --> 00:50:53,260
But the production value
was, yeah, a slight nightmare.

1083
00:50:53,427 --> 00:50:55,262
PELL: Yes, this was a
major, major sequence

1084
00:50:55,346 --> 00:50:57,346
that kept everyone busy for a long time.

1085
00:50:57,640 --> 00:50:58,765
MUSKER: Many, many
animators worked on this.

1086
00:50:58,849 --> 00:50:59,850
PELL: But worked out brilliantly.

1087
00:50:59,934 --> 00:51:02,060
CLEMENTS: Still one
of the earlier things done

1088
00:51:02,144 --> 00:51:05,064
in the movie because it was a song.

1089
00:51:05,814 --> 00:51:10,152
Heard your princess
Was a sight lovely to see

1090
00:51:10,236 --> 00:51:11,820
And that, good people, is why

1091
00:51:11,904 --> 00:51:15,073
MUSKER: The reflections in the
floor, that production is really cool.

1092
00:51:15,157 --> 00:51:17,451
CLEMENTS: Howard always
loved these little lyric things

1093
00:51:17,535 --> 00:51:19,244
where you go through a string of things,

1094
00:51:19,328 --> 00:51:24,082
and that's very Howard in
terms of these quick images.

1095
00:51:24,166 --> 00:51:25,667
Yeah, lightning quick.

1096
00:51:25,751 --> 00:51:27,002
PELL: The list song.

1097
00:51:27,086 --> 00:51:29,212
CLEMENTS: Like Under
the Sea, where he lists

1098
00:51:29,296 --> 00:51:32,048
all the different band of characters

1099
00:51:32,132 --> 00:51:33,383
and of fish.

1100
00:51:33,467 --> 00:51:35,427
<i>Absolutely marvelous.</i>

1101
00:51:35,803 --> 00:51:36,845
[CLEARS THROAT]

1102
00:51:36,929 --> 00:51:38,096
<i>Your Majesty…</i>

1103
00:51:38,180 --> 00:51:40,974
PELL: Prince Ali was
such big production values,

1104
00:51:41,058 --> 00:51:43,852
and our production manager, Alice Dewey,

1105
00:51:43,936 --> 00:51:47,022
really helped coordinate
all of it to get it done.

1106
00:51:47,106 --> 00:51:49,056
I mean, that's true of the whole movie.

1107
00:51:50,234 --> 00:51:52,819
MUSKER: One of the ways
is, in a sequence like this

1108
00:51:52,903 --> 00:51:55,656
now playing, obviously
it's fewer characters,

1109
00:51:55,781 --> 00:51:59,951
we didn't have tones on the characters.
We did have shadows,

1110
00:52:00,035 --> 00:52:03,038
but we tried to restrict the amount
of effects in a scene like this.

1111
00:52:03,122 --> 00:52:05,248
Just sneak as many as
we could get away with in.

1112
00:52:05,332 --> 00:52:07,459
CLEMENTS: It was really a
challenge 'cause budget-wise,

1113
00:52:07,543 --> 00:52:09,336
we were on a pretty strict budget,

1114
00:52:09,420 --> 00:52:13,048
particularly for the
early part of the movie.

1115
00:52:13,674 --> 00:52:17,469
And so it was really trying to
watch everything and pick our spots,

1116
00:52:18,679 --> 00:52:21,806
and Alice and Amy and
everyone really helped

1117
00:52:21,890 --> 00:52:25,394
in terms of putting it where it counted

1118
00:52:26,770 --> 00:52:29,022
and in the most effective way possible.

1119
00:52:29,106 --> 00:52:31,608
MUSKER: This is, yes, our
Masterpiece Theater sequence

1120
00:52:31,692 --> 00:52:32,943
where we insisted on only getting

1121
00:52:33,027 --> 00:52:35,570
the most elevated gags possible in here.

1122
00:52:35,654 --> 00:52:39,115
PELL: One of my favorite gags
is here, where Brian Ferguson

1123
00:52:39,199 --> 00:52:44,455
-animates Iago clunking in.
-MUSKER: This one coming up here?

1124
00:52:44,539 --> 00:52:46,541
PELL: Yes, the one coming up.
CLEMENTS: With the little Sultans?

1125
00:52:46,625 --> 00:52:48,334
PELL: The little Sultans
around his head, yeah.

1126
00:52:48,418 --> 00:52:50,878
MUSKER: Yeah, Brian
Ferguson, another Canadian,

1127
00:52:50,962 --> 00:52:52,797
tall, eccentric Canadian animator.

1128
00:52:52,881 --> 00:52:54,633
CLEMENTS: Yeah, this was Brian.

1129
00:52:55,634 --> 00:52:57,510
<i>Out of the way. I'm coming in to land.</i>

1130
00:52:57,594 --> 00:52:59,428
<i>Jafar, watch this.</i>

1131
00:52:59,512 --> 00:53:01,973
<i>-Spectacular, Your Highness.
-That was lovely.</i>

1132
00:53:03,558 --> 00:53:05,601
MUSKER: That's fun with the
voice actors, like on Douglas Seale,

1133
00:53:05,685 --> 00:53:08,813
when we just had him ad-lib all his…
[WHOOPING] Flying around.

