1356
01:02:38,638 --> 01:02:42,391
<i>For the first time in my life,
things are starting to go right.</i>

1357
01:02:44,268 --> 01:02:45,853
PELL: No, they're not.

1358
01:02:46,938 --> 01:02:48,522
[MUFFLED] Abu. Abu.</i>

1359
01:02:48,606 --> 01:02:51,150
MUSKER: Yes, it's the
ham-on-a-string sequence.

1360
01:02:55,279 --> 01:02:58,324
<i>I'm afraid you've worn out
your welcome, Prince Abubu.</i>

1361
01:02:58,658 --> 01:02:59,950
[MUFFLED] <i>Why, you…</i>

1362
01:03:00,034 --> 01:03:02,495
<i>Make sure he's never found.</i>

1363
01:03:02,912 --> 01:03:05,081
CLEMENTS: A pretty nasty Jafar there.

1364
01:03:06,249 --> 01:03:08,917
This was actually a Ted
and Terry idea, I think.

1365
01:03:09,001 --> 01:03:12,629
Originally, we'd had a different
way that Aladdin was taken out,

1366
01:03:12,713 --> 01:03:17,426
but they wrote this idea of
him being thrown into water,

1367
01:03:17,510 --> 01:03:20,471
and it's pretty uncomfortable, I think.

1368
01:03:36,362 --> 01:03:37,738
MUSKER: Of course, Robin here,

1369
01:03:37,822 --> 01:03:42,910
his whole mock German that he
came up with on this was very funny.

1370
01:03:42,994 --> 01:03:45,537
That was not written to
be German necessarily.

1371
01:03:45,621 --> 01:03:47,039
I think that was Robin's…

1372
01:03:47,123 --> 01:03:49,823
It's coming up, when he
does his submarine thing later.

1373
01:03:50,167 --> 01:03:51,419
<i>Al?</i>

1374
01:03:51,544 --> 01:03:53,337
[GASPING] <i>Al! Kid…</i>

1375
01:03:53,421 --> 01:03:55,631
MUSKER: Actually, all
this calling of Aladdin, "Al,"

1376
01:03:55,715 --> 01:03:57,966
that was something Robin did ad-lib.

1377
01:03:58,050 --> 01:04:00,886
CLEMENTS: In the first
session, he just threw that out.

1378
01:04:00,970 --> 01:04:02,304
MUSKER: And then we wrote to it.
Once we heard it,

1379
01:04:02,388 --> 01:04:04,306
we decided, "Wait, we could
actually take advantage of that"

1380
01:04:04,390 --> 01:04:06,099
"in terms of their relationship"

1381
01:04:06,183 --> 01:04:09,686
"and what Aladdin means
versus Al in terms of the…"

1382
01:04:09,770 --> 01:04:12,420
Yeah, that's his homage
to Sid Caesar, there, I think.

1383
01:04:15,277 --> 01:04:16,736
[COUGHING]

1384
01:04:16,820 --> 01:04:21,908
CLEMENTS: We get their relationship,
a nice, warm moment between them.

1385
01:04:22,159 --> 01:04:24,161
<i>I, uh…</i>

1386
01:04:24,661 --> 01:04:26,204
<i>I…</i>

1387
01:04:27,748 --> 01:04:29,999
<i>-Thanks, Genie.
-Oh, Al.</i>

1388
01:04:30,083 --> 01:04:32,169
<i>I'm gettin' kind of fond of you, kid.</i>

1389
01:04:32,753 --> 01:04:35,130
<i>Not that I wanna pick
out curtains or anything.</i>

1390
01:04:35,964 --> 01:04:38,550
CLEMENTS: A little
controversy about that line.

1391
01:04:41,261 --> 01:04:43,054
SULTAN: <i>Jasmine.</i>

1392
01:04:43,138 --> 01:04:45,848
<i>Oh, Father, I just had
the most wonderful…</i>

1393
01:04:45,932 --> 01:04:49,686
PELL: At first the idea of not
having a mother, we thought,

1394
01:04:49,770 --> 01:04:52,188
"No, every animated movie
doesn't have the parents.

1395
01:04:52,272 --> 01:04:54,357
-"We don't wanna go that route."
-MUSKER: Yeah, here we go again.

1396
01:04:54,441 --> 01:04:55,483
"My mother's gonna kill me."

1397
01:04:55,567 --> 01:04:57,068
PELL: But there is some emotional element

1398
01:04:57,152 --> 01:04:59,821
that worked, especially in
terms of the street urchin.

1399
01:05:02,366 --> 01:05:04,200
MUSKER: Had to prove
himself, the low self-esteem.

1400
01:05:04,284 --> 01:05:06,911
Or the guy who's really
being denigrated on the street,

1401
01:05:06,995 --> 01:05:10,415
and he questions himself, even.
"Am I really the guy they say I am?"

1402
01:05:10,499 --> 01:05:12,709
"And I don't think I am, and I'm
going to prove to people I'm not."

1403
01:05:12,793 --> 01:05:13,876
CLEMENTS: And the
diamond-in-the-rough thing

1404
01:05:13,960 --> 01:05:15,128
kind of resonates, I think.

1405
01:05:15,212 --> 01:05:16,838
Even among teenagers,

1406
01:05:16,922 --> 01:05:21,801
I think there's a thematic
thing there that is valid.

1407
01:05:21,885 --> 01:05:25,096
On the surface, you can seem
like you've really been dealt

1408
01:05:25,180 --> 01:05:26,806
a poor deck of cards,

1409
01:05:26,890 --> 01:05:30,059
but really what's inside is
what's the most important.

1410
01:05:30,143 --> 01:05:33,646
Sometimes people in very
unfortunate circumstances

1411
01:05:33,730 --> 01:05:36,191
can find that they are
a diamond in the rough,

1412
01:05:36,316 --> 01:05:38,943
if they can find what's
inside them that's valuable.

1413
01:05:39,027 --> 01:05:41,195
So I think that message…

1414
01:05:41,279 --> 01:05:43,823
MUSKER: And the basic message
that came through in the rewrite,

1415
01:05:43,907 --> 01:05:46,242
stronger perhaps, was the whole,
just sort of "Be yourself" idea."

1416
01:05:46,326 --> 01:05:47,410
PELL: Owning who you were.

1417
01:05:47,494 --> 01:05:49,662
MUSKER: Really celebrate who you are,

1418
01:05:49,746 --> 01:05:52,623
and don't try and be something else,
which I think is thematically something

1419
01:05:52,707 --> 01:05:56,419
that people, including
teenagers and kids, can relate to,

1420
01:05:56,503 --> 01:05:58,087
just because there's often pressures

1421
01:05:58,171 --> 01:06:00,381
to be something other
than you really are.

1422
01:06:00,465 --> 01:06:01,674
PELL: I also think it's timeless,

1423
01:06:01,758 --> 01:06:04,969
and that's why Aladdin
has stood the test of time.

1424
01:06:05,053 --> 01:06:07,723
MUSKER: I think the
topicality, the humor and that,

1425
01:06:07,807 --> 01:06:10,726
that comes and goes and all that.
But I think the themes work.

1426
01:06:10,810 --> 01:06:15,189
And I do still think it's still funny
today. [CHUCKLING] So that helps.

1427
01:06:17,150 --> 01:06:19,485
CLEMENTS: Some nice
Sultan animation in this,

1428
01:06:19,569 --> 01:06:21,445
and Douglas Seale, again,

1429
01:06:21,529 --> 01:06:24,907
did a nice bit here
where he gets all excited.

1430
01:06:24,991 --> 01:06:27,284
PELL: David Pruiksma.
MUSKER: And Barry Temple as well.

1431
01:06:27,368 --> 01:06:29,661
Barry Temple did some of this in here.
Am I remembering that right?

1432
01:06:29,745 --> 01:06:30,913
CLEMENTS: Yeah.

1433
01:06:30,997 --> 01:06:34,584
Barry Temple was in Florida, so
he actually, probably did this part.

1434
01:06:35,877 --> 01:06:37,878
PELL: But David Pruiksma
was the lead for the character.

1435
01:06:37,962 --> 01:06:39,922
I didn't know if you had
mentioned him earlier or not.

1436
01:06:40,006 --> 01:06:41,965
He was a major
influence on the character.

1437
01:06:42,049 --> 01:06:45,344
CLEMENTS: Once again,
the theme of being trapped.

1438
01:06:45,428 --> 01:06:49,473
I think we were pushing the idea
that you can be trapped by success

1439
01:06:49,557 --> 01:06:53,060
as well as being trapped by failure.

1440
01:06:54,479 --> 01:06:56,313
MUSKER: Jonathan
Freeman, the funny thing is,

1441
01:06:56,397 --> 01:06:59,066
we heard Jonathan Freeman's
voice before we ever saw him.

1442
01:06:59,150 --> 01:07:01,193
He auditioned in New York for the part.

1443
01:07:01,277 --> 01:07:02,403
And we had no idea what he looked like.

1444
01:07:02,487 --> 01:07:04,071
We heard his name and we just thought,

1445
01:07:04,155 --> 01:07:06,365
"Wow, this is a cool,
great dramatic voice,"

1446
01:07:06,449 --> 01:07:09,993
and we pictured this rail-thin,

1447
01:07:10,077 --> 01:07:11,745
whatever, Vincent Price. Whatever.

1448
01:07:11,829 --> 01:07:13,288
CLEMENTS: The voice fits the character

1449
01:07:13,372 --> 01:07:14,998
much more than it fits Jonathan Freeman.

1450
01:07:15,082 --> 01:07:17,084
MUSKER: And then we saw
Jonathan Freeman, and he's handsome,

1451
01:07:17,168 --> 01:07:21,171
but a rounder-than-he-is-angular
sort of a guy,

1452
01:07:21,255 --> 01:07:23,966
and yet he brought such a fun, oily…

1453
01:07:24,050 --> 01:07:25,850
He just went to town with the voice.

1454
01:07:26,719 --> 01:07:28,220
He was a stage actor,

1455
01:07:28,304 --> 01:07:32,683
so he brought a stage actor sense
of timing and delivery and all that.

1456
01:07:32,767 --> 01:07:34,518
And that was really fun for Jafar.

1457
01:07:34,602 --> 01:07:35,978
<i>Huzzah!</i>

1458
01:07:36,062 --> 01:07:38,522
[SINGING] Hail the conquering hero

1459
01:07:38,606 --> 01:07:41,442
CLEMENTS: I wondered if this
gag coming up was going to date,

1460
01:07:41,526 --> 01:07:45,238
but I think people will still get it.

1461
01:07:46,405 --> 01:07:47,406
This is the…

1462
01:07:47,490 --> 01:07:49,366
<i>You've just won the
heart of the princess.</i>

1463
01:07:49,450 --> 01:07:51,076
<i>What are you gonna do next?</i>

1464
01:07:51,160 --> 01:07:52,161
CLEMENTS: They're still doing that?

1465
01:07:52,245 --> 01:07:56,207
MUSKER: Alan did the little
musical quote there. That was fun.

1466
01:07:57,750 --> 01:07:59,793
[WHISPERING] <i>Psst. Your line is…</i>

1467
01:07:59,877 --> 01:08:02,005
MUSKER: This is probably
the biggest breaking

1468
01:08:02,089 --> 01:08:03,381
of the plane we did in the movie,

1469
01:08:03,465 --> 01:08:05,592
where we said, "This is really a movie."

1470
01:08:05,676 --> 01:08:08,970
Reading from the script, and
it was something you don't see

1471
01:08:09,054 --> 01:08:11,389
in most of the others, and
it was a calculated thing.

1472
01:08:11,473 --> 01:08:12,891
CLEMENTS: We actually discuss that stuff,

1473
01:08:12,975 --> 01:08:14,058
even though it's taken for granted,

1474
01:08:14,142 --> 01:08:15,560
just how far can we go?

1475
01:08:15,644 --> 01:08:18,813
How far can we not go?
And I think that actually is the farthest,

1476
01:08:18,897 --> 01:08:21,357
but we felt within that
scene you could do it

1477
01:08:21,441 --> 01:08:23,735
and get away with it.

1478
01:08:24,945 --> 01:08:27,489
Our conceit with the
Genie was basically that

1479
01:08:27,573 --> 01:08:30,492
because he was almost
like a god-like figure

1480
01:08:30,576 --> 01:08:32,243
who transcended space and time,

1481
01:08:32,327 --> 01:08:36,915
he could know all the
cultural references of any time,

1482
01:08:36,999 --> 01:08:39,751
and even though the other
characters wouldn't get his humor at all,

1483
01:08:39,835 --> 01:08:42,462
he somehow thinks that's funny.
But the idea that…

1484
01:08:42,546 --> 01:08:43,713
MUSKER: He's trying to entertain himself

1485
01:08:43,797 --> 01:08:46,257
CLEMENTS: Right, yeah, he's been
cooped up for thousands of years,

1486
01:08:46,341 --> 01:08:50,637
and he has an audience now
and he wants to be entertaining.

1487
01:08:50,721 --> 01:08:53,473
But he's read the script? I mean, that's…

1488
01:08:53,557 --> 01:08:57,393
PELL: I think you both achieved
great emotion in this scene,

1489
01:08:57,477 --> 01:09:03,483
not only with the script, but
the visual of his size going down.

1490
01:09:04,109 --> 01:09:08,196
MUSKER: I think it helped to have
them to cut to, Abu as the elephant

1491
01:09:08,280 --> 01:09:10,698
and the carpet, to get a little
bit more of an audience cue

1492
01:09:10,782 --> 01:09:13,284
and to get more sincerity
and warmth in this.

1493
01:09:13,368 --> 01:09:16,038
PELL: And their disapproval
coming through, too.

1494
01:09:16,413 --> 01:09:18,582
And also puts him alone, again.

1495
01:09:18,707 --> 01:09:22,210
CLEMENTS: Yeah, he's isolated now.
He's gone past where he should be.

1496
01:09:22,294 --> 01:09:23,753
Robin's acting on that

1497
01:09:23,837 --> 01:09:25,838
and Scott's acting was
very strong and sincere.

1498
01:09:25,922 --> 01:09:28,758
And there, again, that was Robin.
When the sincere moments came,

1499
01:09:28,842 --> 01:09:31,692
he played them very straight,
and that was very effective.

1500
01:09:31,887 --> 01:09:34,305
MUSKER: I remember, this sequence,
we fooled around with a little bit.

1501
01:09:34,389 --> 01:09:35,890
Ed Gombert, I think,
came up with the idea

1502
01:09:35,974 --> 01:09:39,978
of this bizarre Iago on the
stilts, posing as a flamingo.

1503
01:09:40,062 --> 01:09:42,189
I seem to remember Ed cooking this up.

1504
01:09:44,066 --> 01:09:46,016
Or at least this gag. I can't remember.

1505
01:09:46,234 --> 01:09:49,487
-[GOOFY CHUCKLE]
<i>-You got a problem, Pinky?</i>

1506
01:09:49,571 --> 01:09:50,697
<i>Jerk.</i>

1507
01:09:50,781 --> 01:09:53,331
-MUSKER: I'm still amused by that.
-[PELL CHUCKLING]

1508
01:09:54,076 --> 01:09:56,538
<i>Boy, Jafar's gonna be happy to see you.</i>

1509
01:09:56,622 --> 01:09:58,206
[IMITATES JAFAR] <i>"Excellent work, Iago."</i>

1510
01:09:58,290 --> 01:09:59,541
<i>Ah, go on.</i>

1511
01:09:59,625 --> 01:10:03,169
<i>"No, really.
On a scale of one to 10, you are an 11 ."</i>

1512
01:10:03,253 --> 01:10:05,255
MUSKER: Our homage to Gary Franklin.

1513
01:10:05,339 --> 01:10:06,506
I don't know, is Gary
Franklin still around?

1514
01:10:06,590 --> 01:10:09,718
He was a film critic out here in
Los Angeles who did a whole scale.

1515
01:10:09,802 --> 01:10:11,928
"On the Franklin scale
of 1 to 10, 10 being best,"

1516
01:10:12,012 --> 01:10:13,179
"I give it a whatever."

1517
01:10:13,263 --> 01:10:14,431
Now there are many critics, I guess,

1518
01:10:14,515 --> 01:10:17,017
but Gary Franklin out here
was the guy that used to do that.

1519
01:10:17,101 --> 01:10:18,810
CLEMENTS: I've always
had parrots as pets,

1520
01:10:18,894 --> 01:10:20,520
and I testify that when they talk,

1521
01:10:20,604 --> 01:10:22,398
they are very good mimics.

1522
01:10:23,357 --> 01:10:24,774
They can actually do that.

1523
01:10:24,858 --> 01:10:26,192
MUSKER: In terms of
their relationship here,

1524
01:10:26,276 --> 01:10:27,819
I do like this little sequence here,

1525
01:10:27,903 --> 01:10:29,362
even with her primping him.

1526
01:10:29,446 --> 01:10:31,698
I've gone through this myself,

1527
01:10:31,782 --> 01:10:34,582
somebody tries to put you
together before you go onstage.

1528
01:10:35,661 --> 01:10:37,663
[CHEERING]

1529
01:10:38,247 --> 01:10:39,706
<i>Look at them…</i>

1530
01:10:39,790 --> 01:10:41,041
PELL: And it was her change of costume,

1531
01:10:41,125 --> 01:10:43,001
where she finally had
her midriff covered.

1532
01:10:43,085 --> 01:10:45,921
CLEMENTS: You were happy
then, I think, Amy, weren't you?

1533
01:10:46,171 --> 01:10:48,381
<i>You know, Al, I'm getting really…</i>

1534
01:10:48,465 --> 01:10:51,551
CLEMENTS: She actually does
have a few changes, but it took a while.

1535
01:10:51,635 --> 01:10:54,387
<i>Will be played by a tall,
dark and sinister ugly man.</i>

1536
01:10:54,471 --> 01:10:57,807
<i>-I am your master now.
-I was afraid of that.</i>

1537
01:10:57,891 --> 01:11:01,102
<i>Genie, grant me my first wish.</i>

1538
01:11:01,186 --> 01:11:02,854
MUSKER: This is where we did…

1539
01:11:02,938 --> 01:11:05,315
A lot of rewriting happened
here from the earlier version

1540
01:11:05,399 --> 01:11:11,321
because, really, there was the
whole idea of Jafar becoming Sultan

1541
01:11:11,405 --> 01:11:14,407
and using the limited
wishes and all that.

1542
01:11:14,491 --> 01:11:16,117
CLEMENTS: This was
really the trickiest part

1543
01:11:16,201 --> 01:11:17,995
of the movie in some ways to solve,

1544
01:11:18,120 --> 01:11:20,622
and I think we had the
whole movie all together

1545
01:11:20,706 --> 01:11:23,583
while we were still struggling
with the story in this part.

1546
01:11:23,667 --> 01:11:26,753
One of the big questions was,
is Jafar going to have a song?

1547
01:11:26,837 --> 01:11:28,213
Can he have a song? We wanted…

1548
01:11:28,297 --> 01:11:30,048
Jonathan Freeman is such a great singer.

1549
01:11:30,132 --> 01:11:31,925
We wanted him to have a song.

1550
01:11:32,009 --> 01:11:33,426
There are actually several versions

1551
01:11:33,510 --> 01:11:36,471
that Alan wrote of a
song here, along with Tim,

1552
01:11:36,555 --> 01:11:39,099
but all of them seemed like

1553
01:11:39,183 --> 01:11:41,935
it just slowed things
down a little bit too much.

1554
01:11:42,019 --> 01:11:45,105
And then finally, I think,
maybe it was Alan who came up

1555
01:11:45,189 --> 01:11:48,858
with just doing the reprise
of the Prince Ali song here.

1556
01:11:48,942 --> 01:11:51,195
MUSKER: I think he felt that the
length of time we were gonna devote

1557
01:11:51,279 --> 01:11:54,824
to this in song had to be brief enough

1558
01:11:54,908 --> 01:11:57,159
that he couldn't come up
with a whole new melody

1559
01:11:57,243 --> 01:11:59,370
and have it land and not
feel like an interruption.

1560
01:11:59,454 --> 01:12:01,455
So he used a reprise of Prince Ali.

1561
01:12:01,539 --> 01:12:03,791
This is Alan's idea to
go back to that melody.

1562
01:12:03,875 --> 01:12:06,544
And I think that worked in
terms of not asking the audience

1563
01:12:06,628 --> 01:12:09,922
to digest a whole new musical motif

1564
01:12:10,006 --> 01:12:12,299
CLEMENTS: At least we got to
hear Jonathan sing for a little bit.

1565
01:12:12,383 --> 01:12:14,635
PELL: But the action is
going so strong at this point,

1566
01:12:14,719 --> 01:12:15,803
you wanna know what's going on.

1567
01:12:15,887 --> 01:12:18,181
MUSKER: We're going
into the third act here.

1568
01:12:18,932 --> 01:12:20,808
PELL: We needed to just
keep it moving at this point.

1569
01:12:20,892 --> 01:12:22,643
MUSKER: Right, you couldn't
stop for a song so much.

1570
01:12:22,727 --> 01:12:26,188
So it had to be a quicker story element.

1571
01:12:26,272 --> 01:12:28,066
<i>Genie, stop!</i>

1572
01:12:29,150 --> 01:12:31,026
<i>Ladies and gentlemen…</i>

1573
01:12:31,110 --> 01:12:33,195
CLEMENTS: That was, I think,
the unique thing about Jafar,

1574
01:12:33,279 --> 01:12:35,948
was he was a malevolent
guy behind the scenes.

1575
01:12:36,032 --> 01:12:38,909
The guy in power, the Sultan,

1576
01:12:38,993 --> 01:12:41,788
is a little bit inept and
a little bit fumbling,

1577
01:12:41,913 --> 01:12:45,708
and it's really the guy behind it,

1578
01:12:45,792 --> 01:12:48,669
the number-two guy, who
secretly wants to be number one.

1579
01:12:48,753 --> 01:12:53,424
And he's so officious
and he's totally two-faced.

1580
01:12:54,175 --> 01:12:56,343
PELL: And, again, all
the colors are changing.

1581
01:12:56,427 --> 01:12:59,055
Even the blues have tints of red.

1582
01:12:59,806 --> 01:13:03,309
[SINGING] Read my lips
And come to grips with reality

1583
01:13:03,393 --> 01:13:05,436
MUSKER: My homage to
Johnny Carson's coming up here,

1584
01:13:05,520 --> 01:13:07,271
with the golf swing at the end.

1585
01:13:07,355 --> 01:13:09,399
Whose lies were too good to last

1586
01:13:09,566 --> 01:13:11,525
CLEMENTS: We always
intended for Jafar to have

1587
01:13:11,609 --> 01:13:13,235
a great villain song in the movie,

1588
01:13:13,319 --> 01:13:17,907
and we went from Humiliate the
Boy to, I think, several other songs.

1589
01:13:17,991 --> 01:13:21,452
I think there were more versions of
the Jafar villain song written for this

1590
01:13:21,536 --> 01:13:23,496
than anything else in the movie.

1591
01:13:23,580 --> 01:13:27,041
We finally settled on a shorter
version of Jafar's villain song

1592
01:13:27,125 --> 01:13:30,795
that actually became just a
reprise of the Prince Ali song.

1593
01:13:31,462 --> 01:13:33,506
Give me adequate cause

1594
01:13:33,673 --> 01:13:36,175
MUSKER: We wanted him to slap
him just to make him that much nastier.

1595
01:13:36,259 --> 01:13:37,927
Give him a little physical abuse.

1596
01:13:38,469 --> 01:13:40,430
He is the bad guy after all.

1597
01:13:41,639 --> 01:13:42,973
Here's the Johnny Carson.

1598
01:13:43,057 --> 01:13:45,185
That was the end of his
monologue all the time.

1599
01:13:45,269 --> 01:13:47,562
No one would care, but I…

1600
01:13:47,646 --> 01:13:50,982
CLEMENTS: Well, also, Iago does
little Ed McMahon bits throughout,

1601
01:13:51,066 --> 01:13:53,068
so there's a lot of references.

1602
01:13:54,111 --> 01:13:56,905
PELL: That wonderful laugh at
the end that Jonathan… It's so great.

1603
01:13:56,989 --> 01:14:00,909
CLEMENTS: He loved the laugh.
Could not get enough of that.

1604
01:14:00,993 --> 01:14:02,953
MUSKER: This was
animated in Florida, again.

1605
01:14:03,037 --> 01:14:07,791
Rob Bekuhrs was the
CG supervisor in Florida

1606
01:14:07,875 --> 01:14:12,921
who animated this whole
parapet tumbling down the slope.

1607
01:14:13,005 --> 01:14:15,590
We did want to get snow just 'cause
we thought it was such a contrast

1608
01:14:15,674 --> 01:14:17,592
with the desert
environment we had been in,

1609
01:14:17,676 --> 01:14:19,261
and you'd been in that for so long.

1610
01:14:19,345 --> 01:14:22,806
It was just nice to get away
and to make it this exotic,

1611
01:14:22,890 --> 01:14:24,599
completely foreign locale.

1612
01:14:24,683 --> 01:14:28,186
CLEMENTS: So this was really
some of the first sequences animated

1613
01:14:28,270 --> 01:14:29,312
by the Florida studio,

1614
01:14:29,396 --> 01:14:33,775
then they went on to do
Mulan and Lilo & Stitch.

1615
01:14:33,859 --> 01:14:35,277
MUSKER: Yeah, full movies.

1616
01:14:35,361 --> 01:14:36,778
I mean, this was
sequences within a movie,

1617
01:14:36,862 --> 01:14:40,366
and ultimately they did their own
films and did a great job on those.

1618
01:14:41,325 --> 01:14:43,577
PELL: This was another
very emotional moment,

1619
01:14:43,661 --> 01:14:45,787
when his best buddy is in danger.

1620
01:14:45,871 --> 01:14:49,332
It just adds to the humanity of Aladdin.

1621
01:14:49,416 --> 01:14:51,960
MUSKER: Right, makes
him more likeable here.

1622
01:14:52,044 --> 01:14:53,170
<i>Carpet.</i>

1623
01:14:53,462 --> 01:14:54,662
MUSKER: Poor old carpet.

1624
01:14:55,297 --> 01:14:59,634
CLEMENTS: I think this gag coming
up is based on a Buster Keaton bit.

1625
01:14:59,718 --> 01:15:02,012
MUSKER: Where the house falls around him,

1626
01:15:02,096 --> 01:15:03,263
and he manages to be standing.

1627
01:15:03,347 --> 01:15:06,297
It's great, one of the classic
sight gags of the silent era.

1628
01:15:08,310 --> 01:15:10,229
-And we stole it.
-[CHUCKLING]

1629
01:15:15,901 --> 01:15:17,485
CLEMENTS: Although
here it's not so much a gag

1630
01:15:17,569 --> 01:15:19,362
as how clever Aladdin is to figure out…

1631
01:15:19,446 --> 01:15:21,281
How clever is he to watch that…

1632
01:15:22,533 --> 01:15:25,243
MUSKER: Richard Vander
Wende was this unbelievable painter.

1633
01:15:25,327 --> 01:15:28,371
His command of light and
shadow and reflected light

1634
01:15:28,455 --> 01:15:30,832
and his rendering skills
were the most amazing thing.

1635
01:15:30,916 --> 01:15:32,834
CLEMENTS: Color. His color sensibility.

1636
01:15:32,918 --> 01:15:34,968
MUSKER: His colors were just exceptional.

1637
01:15:35,337 --> 01:15:38,006
CLEMENTS: Now everything is
red, 'cause Jafar has taken over,

1638
01:15:38,090 --> 01:15:42,303
so the progression of red has
consumed the movie at this point.

1639
01:15:42,554 --> 01:15:44,639
PELL: And also, the columns in the palace

1640
01:15:44,723 --> 01:15:47,934
are much more elongated
than when the Sultan was there.

1641
01:15:48,601 --> 01:15:50,853
CLEMENTS: Yeah, he redesigned everything.

1642
01:15:50,937 --> 01:15:53,439
MUSKER: Sue Nichols, our
storyboard artist, did this sequence,

1643
01:15:53,523 --> 01:15:55,483
and she did a lot of
great stuff in the boards

1644
01:15:55,567 --> 01:15:57,276
that then we tried to
get in the animation,

1645
01:15:57,360 --> 01:16:00,780
in terms of some of the
attitudes here and the ideas.

1646
01:16:00,864 --> 01:16:06,661
His repellent attempts
to take advantage of her.

1647
01:16:08,163 --> 01:16:10,623
<i>I'll teach you some respect.</i>

1648
01:16:11,249 --> 01:16:12,250
CLEMENTS: Nasty.

1649
01:16:13,084 --> 01:16:15,128
<i>No. Genie.</i>

1650
01:16:16,463 --> 01:16:18,506
<i>I have decided to make my final wish.</i>

1651
01:16:18,590 --> 01:16:21,258
MUSKER: A subdued Genie,
something we haven't seen very much.

1652
01:16:21,342 --> 01:16:22,802
He's a beaten guy.

1653
01:16:24,429 --> 01:16:26,055
CLEMENTS: And the second appearance

1654
01:16:26,139 --> 01:16:28,808
of William F. Buckley is coming up.

1655
01:16:29,225 --> 01:16:30,643
MUSKER: You didn't have enough.

1656
01:16:30,727 --> 01:16:34,146
-There was a groundswell…
-CLEMENTS: Yes, we gotta have more

1657
01:16:34,230 --> 01:16:35,940
-William F. Buckley.
-of conservative Republicans

1658
01:16:36,024 --> 01:16:39,324
who wanted… The National Review
readership was demanding, please.

1659
01:16:40,111 --> 01:16:41,362
CLEMENTS: I know when we first brought

1660
01:16:41,446 --> 01:16:42,571
Robin in and we worked with him,

1661
01:16:42,655 --> 01:16:46,409
there was some question if he
should do some sort of persona

1662
01:16:46,493 --> 01:16:48,577
as the Genie in neutral.

1663
01:16:48,661 --> 01:16:51,206
If he should have an Arabian accent

1664
01:16:51,331 --> 01:16:52,707
or play him as a character.

1665
01:16:52,791 --> 01:16:55,042
I think we tried a few things,
but it seemed really obvious

1666
01:16:55,126 --> 01:16:58,546
that, no, the Genie is
Robin in his own mode.

1667
01:16:58,630 --> 01:17:01,132
You think of a personality like Robin,

1668
01:17:01,216 --> 01:17:03,426
if he were trapped in some sort of prison

1669
01:17:03,510 --> 01:17:06,929
for years and years and years,
just what a sad thing that is,

1670
01:17:07,013 --> 01:17:09,640
just because of the
energy and the impulse

1671
01:17:09,724 --> 01:17:12,560
to just entertain and be a bright light.

1672
01:17:16,356 --> 01:17:19,316
We have all the stuff we did
with Robin that we didn't use.

1673
01:17:19,400 --> 01:17:22,862
I think there was probably
more recorded for this sequence

1674
01:17:22,946 --> 01:17:25,406
than any other part of the movie.

1675
01:17:25,949 --> 01:17:28,993
<i>JASMINE: Cute little
gaps between your teeth.</i>

1676
01:17:29,369 --> 01:17:30,619
MUSKER: We had him cheering Aladdin on.

1677
01:17:30,703 --> 01:17:31,912
He did all sorts of variations.

1678
01:17:31,996 --> 01:17:35,459
He was Patton. He was Sylvester Stallone.

1679
01:17:35,543 --> 01:17:37,962
A fight promoter.

1680
01:17:38,087 --> 01:17:39,796
CLEMENTS: We actually
ran the whole sequence

1681
01:17:39,880 --> 01:17:41,048
for him in storyboard form,

1682
01:17:41,132 --> 01:17:42,591
and he would just do commentary.

1683
01:17:42,675 --> 01:17:44,176
MUSKER: Howard Cosell.

1684
01:17:44,260 --> 01:17:46,636
CLEMENTS: He did tons
of totally hilarious stuff,

1685
01:17:46,720 --> 01:17:48,805
and in the end, we only
used just a smidgen,

1686
01:17:48,889 --> 01:17:53,018
'cause it just felt like if we got
too carried away with the Genie,

1687
01:17:53,102 --> 01:17:57,022
it would take away from the
seriousness of the situation here.

1688
01:17:57,106 --> 01:17:58,648
MUSKER: Most horrifying
scene in the movie there,

1689
01:17:58,732 --> 01:18:00,150
the kiss with the bad guy.

1690
01:18:00,234 --> 01:18:02,194
Fortunately, the monkey
could react like we did.

1691
01:18:02,278 --> 01:18:03,779
CLEMENTS: Like the whole audience did.

1692
01:18:03,863 --> 01:18:05,655
MUSKER: The audience
did give a big vocal reaction.

1693
01:18:05,739 --> 01:18:09,689
We were trying to work with their reaction
and let it play out for a little bit.

1694
01:18:14,206 --> 01:18:15,416
<i>Get the lamp.</i>

1695
01:18:16,876 --> 01:18:18,335
<i>No!</i>

1696
01:18:18,586 --> 01:18:21,797
<i>Ah, ah, ah, Princess. Your time is up.</i>

1697
01:18:22,006 --> 01:18:23,840
MUSKER: He's doing his
James Bond villain lines.

1698
01:18:23,924 --> 01:18:26,593
CLEMENTS: A lot of puns, a lot of puns.
MUSKER: Just kill them with puns.

1699
01:18:26,677 --> 01:18:27,719
It always works.

1700
01:18:27,803 --> 01:18:30,097
<i>Oh, nice shot, Jaf…</i>

1701
01:18:32,057 --> 01:18:34,226
<i>Don't toy with me.</i>

1702
01:18:34,310 --> 01:18:35,519
MUSKER: Another one.

1703
01:18:35,603 --> 01:18:36,686
<i>Abu!</i>

1704
01:18:36,770 --> 01:18:38,563
JAFAR: <i>Things are unraveling fast now…</i>

1705
01:18:38,647 --> 01:18:41,483
MUSKER: [CHUCKLING] He won't stop.
It's just…

1706
01:18:42,860 --> 01:18:44,486
<i>Get the point?</i>

1707
01:18:44,778 --> 01:18:46,571
[LAUGHING]

1708
01:18:46,655 --> 01:18:48,240
[STRAINING]

1709
01:18:50,326 --> 01:18:52,369
<i>I'm just getting warmed up.</i>

1710
01:18:52,536 --> 01:18:53,870
[LAUGHTER]

1711
01:18:53,954 --> 01:18:58,292
MUSKER: Okay.
It's not Eugene O'Neill, all right?

1712
01:18:59,210 --> 01:19:02,379
CLEMENTS: It's Jafar's character.
He just loves those.

1713
01:19:03,172 --> 01:19:04,924
Take my villain, please.

1714
01:19:06,175 --> 01:19:07,217
MUSKER: So now this
is where we talk about

1715
01:19:07,301 --> 01:19:09,886
Kathy Zielinski animated this
scene of him transitioning into a snake

1716
01:19:09,970 --> 01:19:13,807
just as she was about to give
birth to her daughter Jennifer, I think.

1717
01:19:15,017 --> 01:19:17,894
Her water broke as she was
animating this, I think, it was.

1718
01:19:17,978 --> 01:19:21,190
AMY: She handed in her final
scene, and then her water broke.

1719
01:19:21,315 --> 01:19:23,984
MUSKER: All for the cause.
Way to go, Kath.

1720
01:19:24,109 --> 01:19:25,152
[SINGING] Rick 'em,
rack 'em, rock 'em, rake

1721
01:19:25,236 --> 01:19:26,361
Stick that sword into that snake

1722
01:19:26,445 --> 01:19:28,071
<i>You stay out of this.</i>

1723
01:19:28,155 --> 01:19:31,409
<i>Jafar, Jafar, he's our man.
If he can't do it… Great!</i>

1724
01:19:32,452 --> 01:19:36,247
MUSKER: In films, often in the third act,
you have what's called a ticking clock,

1725
01:19:36,331 --> 01:19:38,082
where you're trying to
prevent something happening

1726
01:19:38,166 --> 01:19:41,127
and you're cutting to something
that's marking time going by.

1727
01:19:41,211 --> 01:19:42,336
So here we have a literal one

1728
01:19:42,420 --> 01:19:45,339
with the hourglass,
which helped achieve that.

1729
01:19:45,423 --> 01:19:46,424
PELL: A literal.

1730
01:19:46,508 --> 01:19:49,594
MUSKER: A literal or
a silent ticking clock.

1731
01:19:53,098 --> 01:19:54,599
CLEMENTS: And then Andreas did

1732
01:19:54,683 --> 01:19:57,435
a lot of the climactic
stuff with the snake.

1733
01:19:57,519 --> 01:20:03,483
MUSKER: Yeah, the snake. It was
fun to reinterpret Jafar as this reptile.

1734
01:20:04,276 --> 01:20:08,446
<i>Without the genie, boy, you're nothing.</i>

1735
01:20:09,531 --> 01:20:12,992
PELL: I know that we were
concerned at one point, how scary is it?

1736
01:20:13,076 --> 01:20:14,452
Is it too scary for kids?

1737
01:20:14,536 --> 01:20:16,287
But, ultimately, I think
we found the balance.

1738
01:20:16,371 --> 01:20:17,705
MUSKER: We tried to leaven it with humor

1739
01:20:17,789 --> 01:20:20,917
and make a balance between
the scariness and the humor.

1740
01:20:21,001 --> 01:20:24,713
<i>Face it, Jafar.
You're still just second best.</i>

1741
01:20:24,963 --> 01:20:27,381
CLEMENTS: We were really
worried as this was going in front

1742
01:20:27,465 --> 01:20:31,011
of the ratings board if
we would get a PG rating.

1743
01:20:31,928 --> 01:20:34,430
And we were relieved
when we got a G rating.

1744
01:20:34,514 --> 01:20:37,642
But at the same time a little
disappointed. [LAUGHING]

1745
01:20:37,726 --> 01:20:41,771
Maybe this wasn't as
powerful as we wanted it to be.

1746
01:20:41,855 --> 01:20:43,981
MUSKER: So we demanded
a recount, didn't we?

1747
01:20:44,065 --> 01:20:45,442
<i>Genie!</i>

1748
01:20:49,237 --> 01:20:52,824
<i>All right, your wish is my command.
Way to go, Al.</i>

1749
01:20:53,950 --> 01:20:55,409
CLEMENTS: Ted Elliott
and Terry Rossio, the writers,

1750
01:20:55,493 --> 01:20:56,911
came up with this bit at the end

1751
01:20:56,995 --> 01:20:59,121
where Aladdin tricks Jafar.

1752
01:20:59,205 --> 01:21:01,999
It was set up earlier in the
movie, where they have the line,

1753
01:21:02,083 --> 01:21:03,751
"It's all part and parcel
of the whole genie biz,"

1754
01:21:03,835 --> 01:21:06,671
"phenomenal cosmic powers…
Itty bitty living space."

1755
01:21:06,755 --> 01:21:09,423
And Aladdin turns that on Jafar here.

1756
01:21:09,507 --> 01:21:13,011
So that the idea is that
becoming a genie means

1757
01:21:13,511 --> 01:21:15,138
that you have to live in a lamp.

1758
01:21:16,389 --> 01:21:21,144
<i>The universe is mine
to command, to control!</i>

1759
01:21:22,395 --> 01:21:24,021
MUSKER: It's the
downside of being a genie.

1760
01:21:24,105 --> 01:21:25,649
CLEMENTS: It's his way of tricking Jafar.

1761
01:21:25,733 --> 01:21:28,360
<i>You wanted to be a genie, you got it.</i>

1762
01:21:28,444 --> 01:21:29,653
<i>What?</i>

1763
01:21:29,737 --> 01:21:31,864
<i>And everything that goes with it.</i>

1764
01:21:32,615 --> 01:21:35,158
CLEMENTS: It can't be fun
being cooped up in that lamp

1765
01:21:35,242 --> 01:21:37,953
with Gilbert Gottfried for all eternity.

1766
01:21:38,037 --> 01:21:40,747
<i>You're the genie. I don't want…</i>

1767
01:21:40,831 --> 01:21:42,249
<i>Itty bitty living space.</i>

1768
01:21:42,625 --> 01:21:45,544
<i>Al, you little genius, you.</i>

1769
01:21:48,381 --> 01:21:50,215
MUSKER: The magic
of animation restoration.

1770
01:21:50,299 --> 01:21:51,467
[CHUCKLING]

1771
01:21:52,301 --> 01:21:55,053
CLEMENTS: I know there was huge
concern as we got into color timing

1772
01:21:55,137 --> 01:21:57,932
and doing our first
release prints of the movie.

1773
01:21:58,140 --> 01:22:00,976
It was tricky to retain
the color intensity,

1774
01:22:01,060 --> 01:22:03,937
particularly of some
of the reds that we had.

1775
01:22:04,021 --> 01:22:06,106
I think Richard was concerned about it.

1776
01:22:06,190 --> 01:22:09,443
Even to maintain from
answer print to release print,

1777
01:22:09,527 --> 01:22:11,778
which is what goes out into the theaters,

1778
01:22:11,862 --> 01:22:16,367
that there was danger of
not getting the full effect.

1779
01:22:19,620 --> 01:22:21,788
Very nice musical bit here, too.

1780
01:22:21,872 --> 01:22:25,584
Some nice animation
as we get into the finale.

1781
01:22:25,668 --> 01:22:26,919
<i>About being a prince.</i>

1782
01:22:27,420 --> 01:22:28,796
<i>I know why you did.</i>

1783
01:22:30,631 --> 01:22:32,675
<i>Well, I guess…</i>

1784
01:22:32,883 --> 01:22:34,926
PELL: There was a lot of
discussion about the ending,

1785
01:22:35,010 --> 01:22:37,680
whether it should end
in a wedding or not.

1786
01:22:38,347 --> 01:22:40,432
MUSKER: At one point, with
Howard Ashman's original reprise,

1787
01:22:40,516 --> 01:22:43,352
there was a wedding, and
people were invited or something,

1788
01:22:43,436 --> 01:22:45,437
but we weren't sure, like,
"Should we do that or not?"

1789
01:22:45,521 --> 01:22:46,855
'Cause there was a question,

1790
01:22:46,939 --> 01:22:48,732
"Was the narrator gonna
come back at the end?"

1791
01:22:48,816 --> 01:22:50,359
It was all back and forth.

1792
01:22:50,443 --> 01:22:53,362
<i>Hey, it's only an eternity of servitude.</i>

1793
01:22:53,571 --> 01:22:55,489
<i>This is love.</i>

1794
01:22:55,573 --> 01:22:59,869
<i>Al, you're not gonna find another
girl like her in a million years.</i>

1795
01:23:00,703 --> 01:23:03,622
CLEMENTS: When we did this,
we weren't expecting any sequels,

1796
01:23:03,706 --> 01:23:06,541
and there have been
a couple video sequels

1797
01:23:06,625 --> 01:23:08,418
to Aladdin done since then.

1798
01:23:08,502 --> 01:23:13,131
Which is good because what
happens at the end is vague.

1799
01:23:13,215 --> 01:23:16,927
I mean, it almost implies a
wedding, but not completely.

1800
01:23:17,887 --> 01:23:19,487
MUSKER: Yeah, it's not explicit.

1801
01:23:19,723 --> 01:23:22,100
<i>Genie, you're free.</i>

1802
01:23:29,316 --> 01:23:31,651
MUSKER: We were trying
to look for a visual symbol

1803
01:23:31,735 --> 01:23:33,861
to symbolize his
freedom from his shackles,

